                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d217">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.003 Wallace, Henry A./78: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harriman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-06-26">June 26,
                            1944</date>.<lb/>[Received June 27—12:51 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2283. <hi rend="italic">Free Press</hi> for June 25 published a despatch dated
                    London, June 24 regarding joint Wallace–Chiang Kai-shek declaration<note n="46"
                        xml:id="d217fn46">Not found in Department files; for text, see press release
                        issued by the Chinese News Service in Chungking, <hi rend="italic">New York
                            Times</hi>, June 25, 1944, p. 19, col. 1.</note> reading in translation
                    as follows: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“According to a Reuter’s report from Chungking as a result of the visit
                            of the Vice President of the United States, Wallace, to Chungking a
                            joint declaration has been published in which it is stated that Wallace
                            and Chiang Kai-shek have considered problems of mutual interest and have
                            come to an agreement regarding fundamental principles and purposes. It
                            is emphasized in the declaration that mutual aid in the war against
                            Japan is the basic factor in Chinese-American relations.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Harriman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
